\begin{IDEA}
**Title**: Simulation-Based Inference of Baryonic Feedback via Differentiable Component Separation

**Description**: This objective implements a conditional normalizing flow (CNF) to solve the inverse problem of mapping frequency-dependent stacked observations to the latent ground-truth components (tSZ, kSZ, and Lensed-CMB). To mitigate the bias introduced by frequency-dependent beam convolution (FWHM 1.0'–4.72'), the architecture incorporates a multi-scale U-Net backbone that learns an implicit deconvolution operator, ensuring the physical signal is disentangled from instrument-induced spatial correlations. The model will be trained on the FLAMINGO L1_m9 HYDRO_FIDUCIAL dataset using a likelihood-free inference framework that minimizes the Kullback–Leibler divergence between the predicted posterior and the true component distributions. By conditioning the flow on specific frequency-dependent noise realizations (SO LAT and Planck FFP10), the framework produces a robust, per-pixel posterior $P(\text{components} | \text{data}, \text{noise})$, quantifying the uncertainty in baryonic feedback signatures. This approach transforms the component separation task from a linear inversion to a generative posterior estimation, effectively isolating non-Gaussian tSZ and kSZ signals from the Gaussian CMB background.
\end{IDEA}


